In Week 41, the pattern that had been forming for months came into sharper relief. The shutdown was no longer just a budget fight; it had become a governing method. Immigration enforcement was no longer just a policy domain; it was a stage for militarized theater and ideological sorting. And the economy was no longer a neutral backdrop; it was a field where public hardship and private gain were braided together. Across these fronts, the same logic appeared: centralize power in the executive, strip neutral capacity out of the civil service, and convert crisis into opportunity for those closest to the president. The Democracy Clock, already deep into the evening, registered only a small movement this week, but the character of that movement mattered. It reflected not a single shock, but the steady tightening of a system in which law, money, and force were bent toward the preservation of one man\'92s power and the enrichment of his circle.\
