The same pattern of personal and financial entanglement appeared in the realm of law. In the space of a few days, Trump pardoned Changpeng Zhao, the Binance founder who had pleaded guilty to major anti\'96money laundering violations, and his administration moved to enable trading of Trump-linked cryptocurrencies on Binance\'92s U.S. exchange. The pardon came after a $2 billion investment from a foreign fund into a stablecoin tied to Trump\'92s family venture, and after Zhao had hired a lobbyist close to Trump\'92s son. Senators from both parties demanded answers from the attorney general, warning that the move signaled to white-collar criminals that loyalty and money could purchase impunity. At the same time, Trump filed a claim seeking $230 million from the Justice Department for supposed persecution by past investigations, with the officials reviewing his demand drawn from his own circle of appointees and former lawyers. Wealth did not just buy access; it now appeared to buy law itself. The trait that tracks this dynamic\'97wealth buying not only speech but legal outcomes\'97rose sharply, because the week\'92s events showed clemency and compensation being treated as chips in a private game.\
