Beneath these headline acts, the civil service was being reshaped to fit the same mold. At the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, a reduction in force during the shutdown wiped out a quarter of the workforce, including the ethics office, the institutional review board, and the Washington office that briefed Congress. Courts had already ruled that earlier terminations of probationary staff went too far, and unions were back in court arguing that the new layoffs were illegal. Yet the notices went out anyway, leaving legally mandated functions without staff and public health capacity in limbo. At the State Department, the Bureau of Population, Refugees, and Migration was restructured to include an \'93office of remigration,\'94 and the Bureau of Consular Affairs was handed to members of a conservative fellowship aligned with Stephen Miller\'92s agenda. At ICE, at least a dozen field office directors were removed and replaced with Border Patrol and CBP hardliners, while in Texas the agency explored privatizing deportation transport, arming contractors to move detainees across 254 counties. These moves were not random. They replaced neutral administrators with ideologues and shifted core state functions into private or partisan hands. The trait that measures politicized and privatized civil service rose because of this deliberate hollowing out.\
