Immigration policy became the sharpest edge of this new order. Stephen Miller, now the White House\'92s homeland security adviser, ran daily secret calls with a small group of conservative diplomats to direct visa revocations and deportations, focusing on critics of Israel and other political targets. Under his guidance, the State Department revoked thousands of visas, many for students, and expanded bans to immigrants from nineteen countries. The administration announced that the United States would accept only 7,500 refugees in the coming year, with a stated preference for white South Africans. ICE and Border Patrol, newly intertwined, pushed into cities with Black Hawk helicopters and tear gas, conducting raids that left a Honduran immigrant dead on a Virginia highway and children choking at a Halloween parade in Chicago. A British Muslim journalist, Sami Hamdi, was detained at San Francisco airport after pro-Israel activists boasted of pressuring officials; his visa was revoked and he was held in a remote detention center. A Nobel laureate, Wole Soyinka, saw his visa pulled after years of criticizing Trump. Citizenship and the right to be present on U.S. soil were no longer neutral legal statuses. They were stratified by origin, ideology, and perceived loyalty.\
