The security apparatus that carried out these policies was being retooled for domestic control. Border Patrol agents, traditionally focused on the frontier, were deployed in force to cities like Los Angeles, Chicago, and New York, using military-style tactics in residential neighborhoods. Masked federal agents conducted street arrests, pulling people into unmarked vehicles. A Guardian investigation uncovered secret ICE holding rooms in federal buildings where detainees were kept for days or weeks, despite internal policies limiting such stays to hours. In Chicago, federal agents fired chemical irritants into a crowd at a Halloween parade while detaining an undocumented immigrant, prompting a federal judge to order a senior Border Patrol official to appear in court daily and wear a body camera. That order was quickly stayed by the Seventh Circuit, narrowing judicial oversight just as raids intensified. Meanwhile, a Pentagon memo, following an August executive order, instructed National Guard units in all fifty states and territories to form \'93quick reaction forces\'94 trained in riot control, with 23,500 troops to be ready for rapid deployment by January. The line between policing and war, between public safety and regime protection, grew thinner.\
