Abroad, the same willingness to wield force with limited constraint was visible. At Trump\'92s direction, the Defense Department conducted lethal strikes on boats in the Caribbean and Eastern Pacific, labeling them terrorist or narcotics traffickers. At least fourteen people were killed in one set of strikes; a survivor rescued by Mexico told a different story, and the Colombian president confirmed that civilians had died in operations off his coast. The aircraft carrier USS Gerald R. Ford and its strike group were sent to the Caribbean, ostensibly to interdict fast boats off Venezuela, with more than 4,000 personnel and ninety combat aircraft involved. Reports suggested that the administration was preparing to shift operations ashore, even as Russian Wagner mercenaries arrived in Venezuela. The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights called the maritime strikes \'93unacceptable\'94 and demanded an investigation. At the same time, Trump announced that the United States would resume nuclear weapons testing for the first time in thirty-three years, framing it as a necessary response to Russia and China. These decisions, taken without visible congressional debate, concentrated war-making power in the executive and normalized the use of high-risk military tools as instruments of personal and political strategy.\
