The shutdown, now in its fourth week, provided the domestic backdrop for all of this. Federal workers lined up at food banks as paychecks stopped. Air traffic controllers and TSA officers worked without pay, leading to staffing shortages and ground stops at major airports. The House of Representatives, under Speaker Mike Johnson, adjourned for most of the period, logging only twenty working days in seventeen weeks and declining to take up measures that might reopen the government or release high-profile investigative files. The Senate, for its part, failed repeatedly to advance a Republican-backed funding bill that omitted healthcare priorities and cut congressionally approved programs. Democrats insisted that any short-term deal include an extension of enhanced Affordable Care Act subsidies, warning that nearly five million people could lose coverage in 2026. The shutdown was not treated as an emergency to be resolved. It was treated as a lever to reshape the state.\
