Nowhere was that clearer than in the fight over food assistance. The Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program, which serves about 42 million Americans, was set to run out of funds on November 1. USDA had roughly $5\'966 billion in a contingency account and had issued guidance on September 30 stating that these funds could be used to continue benefits during a shutdown, consistent with past practice. In late October, the department reversed course, declared that the money was legally unavailable, and quietly removed the guidance from its website. A banner blaming the \'93Radical Left Democrat shutdown\'94 appeared on the Food and Nutrition Service homepage, and another USDA page scapegoated trans people and \'93illegal aliens\'94 for the funding lapse. The administration refused to tap the contingency fund even as it negotiated a $40 billion currency swap and bailout package for Argentina. States, cities, and advocacy groups sued, arguing that USDA\'92s position was unlawful and that cutting off SNAP would harm children\'92s development, local economies, and basic public health.\
\
The courts, in this domain, pushed back. Judges in Rhode Island and Massachusetts issued orders blocking the suspension of SNAP benefits, finding that the administration\'92s legal arguments were likely wrong and that the harm to low-income households would be severe. A federal judge in Boston demanded that the government submit a plan to partially fund SNAP by the following Monday. Another judge in Rhode Island ordered USDA to distribute contingency funds for November 1 payments. Popular reporting emphasized that 20 million children were among those at risk. These rulings did not resolve the shutdown or repair the underlying political dysfunction, but they did force the executive to honor existing statutory commitments, at least temporarily. They also underscored a broader pattern: courts were increasingly the last line of defense for basic social rights, stepping in where Congress had failed to act.\
\
Even as the shutdown squeezed the poor, it opened channels for profit and influence at the top. Timothy Mellon\'92s $130 million donation to help pay troops during the shutdown covered less than seven hours of military payroll but set a precedent: a billionaire could step into a core state function and, in doing so, deepen his relationship with the commander in chief. The Trump family\'92s crypto ventures generated $864 million in the first half of the year, much of it from the sale of World Liberty tokens, with foreign investors\'97including a Chinese businessman under money-laundering investigation\'97courted by Eric Trump. After Zhao\'92s pardon, Binance\'92s U.S. exchange announced it would list two Trump-linked tokens, USD1 and WLFI, creating a direct financial upside for the president from a regulatory decision. The Pentagon\'92s drone contract to Unusual Machines, where Donald Trump Jr. served as an adviser and shareholder, further blurred the line between public procurement and family business. In each case, crisis and policy were not just managed. They were monetized.\
