Here, too, courts and some institutions resisted. A federal judge blocked enforcement of an executive order provision that would have required proof of citizenship on federal voter registration forms, finding it likely unlawful. The Department of Justice announced plans to monitor polling sites in six jurisdictions during the upcoming elections, a traditional measure to deter intimidation. In California, voters would have the chance to accept or reject Proposition 50 at the ballot box. Yet the broader trend was clear. Structural tools\'97redistricting, registration rules, prosecutorial discretion\'97were being used to shape who could vote, whose votes counted, and which narratives about past elections would be treated as legitimate. The trait that tracks opposition parties being allowed but structurally weakened ticked upward, not because opposition was banned, but because the playing field was being tilted under their feet.\
