Information itself was under pressure from multiple directions. Bill Owens, the former executive producer of 60 Minutes, described how corporate bosses at Paramount had leaned on him to avoid stories on Gaza and Trump, and to apologize for an edited interview with Kamala Harris. He refused and resigned, calling it censorship tied to a pending merger. A Trump-appointed regulator reportedly threatened ABC in ways that contributed to Jimmy Kimmel\'92s suspension, signaling that broadcast licenses could be used as levers against critical voices. At George Mason University, administrators demanded that Students for Justice in Palestine remove a video describing Israel as a \'93genocidal Zionist state,\'94 citing the IHRA definition of antisemitism; the students threatened to sue, arguing that their First Amendment rights were being violated. The USDA\'92s website, as noted, carried partisan and scapegoating messages about the shutdown before quietly erasing guidance that contradicted the administration\'92s line. Together, these episodes showed how corporate, regulatory, and institutional pressures were narrowing the space for dissenting narratives.\
