Amid this, there were still signs of institutional resilience. Environmental and communications regulators continued to issue technical rules on pesticides, ozone standards, air emissions reporting, and submarine cable security, with public comment periods and detailed justifications. European NATO members increased defense spending in response to Russian aggression, and Japan, under its new prime minister, pursued structural economic reforms and defense industry development within a democratic framework. In the United States, state attorneys general built new tools to document federal abuses, and unions and civil rights groups used the courts to challenge layoffs, detention conditions, and voting barriers. These actions did not reverse the week\'92s authoritarian drift, but they preserved channels through which future repair might be attempted.\
