Looking ahead from Week 41, several processes were already in motion. The lawsuits over SNAP funding would continue through appeals, testing whether the emergency use of social programs as bargaining chips could be constrained by law. The en banc rehearing in the Ninth Circuit on Trump\'92s authority to deploy the National Guard in Portland would shape the boundary between federal and state control over domestic military force. The creation of National Guard quick reaction forces, scheduled to be operational by January, would move from planning to practice, with implications for how protests and unrest would be policed in the coming year. The trade frameworks with China and Brazil, and the $40 billion package for Argentina, would pass through internal approval processes, revealing how much of foreign economic policy was driven by coherent strategy and how much by personal grievance or gain. And the planned nationwide economic boycott, \'93Black Out the System,\'94 set for late November, would test whether civil society could still mount large-scale, nonviolent resistance in an environment of increasing surveillance and repression.\
